    "author_association": "MEMBER",
    "body": "## Problem\n\nLogging consumers want to configure \"sinks\" (filesystem, memory, buffered sinks https://github.com/neovim/neovim/pull/39735) for log messages. We could do this via Lua, but then we're reinventing the \"event emitter\" interface that is already provided by autocmds.\n\n## Expected behavior\n\nThe events (autocmds) subsystem already provides an \"event emitter\" interface. We can easily support \"multiple sinks\" if log messages are events, then listeners can subscribe to `LogMsg`. \n\nI'm also wondering if it makes since to use a similar model as we did for Progress messages, i.e. add a new `kind=log` so that \"writing a log\" becomes:\n\n    nvim_echo(..., {kind='log', status='warn', source='my.plugin', data=...})\n\nand that emits a `LogMsg my.plugin` event where `ev.data.data` is set to the `nvim_echo{data}`.\n\n## Open questions\n\n- performance: emitting an event is more expensive (how much?) than calling `vim.log.info()`\n    - but `vim.log.info()` can still be the main interface; internally it calls `nvim_echo`, and then the \"sinks\" handle the message.\n- indicate the loglevel via `kind='log.warn'`, or `title='warn'`, or `status='warn'` ?\n- we probably still need `vim.log` in some form, but perhaps more minimal.\n    - `vim.log` gives performance gains because it can skip calls to `nvim_echo`.",
    "closed_at": null,
    "closed_by": null,
    "comment_data": [
        {
            "author_association": "MEMBER",
            "body": "analysis:\n\n> Conflating logging with display. `nvim_echo` (a message/display API) means every vim.log.debug() either (a) prints to :messages, or (b) gets a special \"don't print\" flag — at which point nvim_echo is just being abused as a transport.\n\nwe are \"abusing\" `nvim_echo` for Progress messages. and yes it's somewhat of a mismatch, but using the same message system as \"transport\" makes sense because they *are* messages and thus should go through the message system.\nand optionally sinking them to `:messages` is a likely use-case.\n\n> Fast-event context. `vim.log.*` is callable from `vim.uv` callbacks and other `vim.in_fast_event()` contexts. Autocmds aren't legal there.\n\n- log messages are not semantically guaranteed to happen at any particular time, so using `aucmd_defer` to emit `LogMsg` is planned.\n  - caveat: If a crash kills nvim before the deferred queue drains, those logs are lost\n\n> Filtering granularity. Autocmd patterns let a sink filter on source (the `pattern`), but not on level.\n\n`vim.log.xx()` will be the interface for log producers, and e.g. `vim.log.info()` will skip `nvim_echo` entirely, so I don't see a need for `LogMsg` subscribers to subscribe to special log-levels.\nHowever, `LogMsg` will include `ev.data.loglevel`. Or we could define `LogMsgError`, `LogMsgWarn`, etc., as distinct events.\n\n> A `level >= WARN` sink pays dispatch cost for every TRACE log. Today level filtering happens at the call site for free.\n\nsee above, that is addressed if `vim.log.xx()` decides dispatch to `nvim_echo`.\n\n> Recursion. If a sink fails and logs the failure (very normal: \"couldn't write to logfile X\"), LogMsg re-fires inside its own handler. Needs an explicit reentrancy guard — not just `nested=false`\n\n- partially addressed by `aucmd_defer`, but doesn't prevent an unbounded queue: handler logs on every invocation → queue refills every tick → CPU-bound livelock.\n  - mitigation?: explicit reentrancy flag (\"this thread is already dispatching LogMsg, drop or queue-with-budget\").\n",
